# Discord Gateway - Systemd Management Guide

This guide explains how to install and manage the Discord Gateway background service on your Server.

## 1. Installation
To install the service on a new server, copy the configuration files to your systemd user directory and enable them:

    mkdir -p ~/.config/systemd/user/
    cp discord.service discord.timer ~/.config/systemd/user/
    systemctl --user daemon-reload
    systemctl --user enable --now discord.timer

## 2. Managing the Service

Start the service immediately (doesn't wait for 3 AM):
    systemctl --user start discord

Stop the service immediately:
    systemctl --user stop discord

Restart the service (useful after replacing the binary with a new version):
    systemctl --user restart discord

Check if the service is currently running:
    systemctl --user status discord

## 3. Managing the Schedule (Timer)

Check when the service is scheduled to run next:
    systemctl --user status discord.timer

Temporarily pause the 3 AM schedule:
    systemctl --user stop discord.timer
    (To stop the whole system from running, remember to stop the service too: systemctl --user stop discord)

Resume the 3 AM schedule:
    systemctl --user start discord.timer

## 4. Reading the Logs

Because we are using systemd, all terminal output is automatically captured by the system journal. You do not need to manage log files manually.

View the live, scrolling output of the service (like tail -f):
    journalctl --user -u discord -f

View the last 100 lines of output:
    journalctl --user -u discord -n 100

View output from today only:
    journalctl --user -u discord --since today
